{"cursor":"2905","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Deirdre Bair' is an American writer and biographer. She is the author of five\nworks of nonfiction.\n\nShe received a National Book Award for [[Samuel Beckett]]: A Biography (1978).\n[http://www.nationalbook.org/nba1981.html \"National Book Awards â 1981\"].\nNational Book Foundation. Retrieved 2012-03-16. Samuel Beckett won the 1981 award for paperback\n\"Autobiography/Biography\". From 1980 to 1983 in National Book Award history\nthere were dual hardcover and paperback awards in most categories, and several\nnonfiction subcategories including General Nonfiction. Most of the paperback award-\nwinners were reprints, including this one. Her biographies of Simone de\nBeauvoir and C. G. Jung were finalists for the Los Angeles Times Book Prize. Her\nbiographies of AnaÃ¯s Nin and Simone de Beauvoir were chosen by the [[New York\nTimes]] as âBest Books of the Yearâ, and her biography of Jung won the Gradiva\nAward from the National Association for the Advancement of Psychoanalysis. Her\nmost recent book, Calling It Quits, examines late-life divorce and starting over\nand has been profiled on CBSâs [[The Early Show]], NBC's [[The Today Show]], the\nBrian Lehrer radio show and on CBC Canada. She is currently working on a\nbiography of New Yorker cartoonist and artist Saul Steinberg.\n\nShe has been awarded fellowships from (among others) the John Simon Guggenheim\nMemorial Foundation, Rockefeller Foundation and the Radcliffe Institute for\nAdvanced Study (then named the Bunting Institute). She is a literary journalist\nwho writes frequently about travel, feminist issue, and cultural life. A former\nprofessor of comparative literature, she writes and lectures internationally but\ndivides her time mostly between New York and Connecticut.\n","linknr":122,"url":"Deirdre_Bair","recorded":1376420300,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Deirdre_Bair&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Deirdre_Bair&action=edit","//bi